{"id":14881865,"mediaExerciseId":"6464bb26-835a-4e46-a5fb-4697e75d2ad7","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"24","chapterTitle":"Options and Corporate Finance","groupId":612498,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":822,"solutions":[{"id":6003619,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine which would sell more if a put option and a call option are available with $30 exercise prices.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define some terms.\n\n- **Put Option** is a contract that gives a holder the right, but not the obligation to sell a stock.\n\n- **Call Option** is a contract that gives a holder the right to buy a stock.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"If a put option and a call option are available with $30 exercise prices, the call option will sell for more because as the stock price rises, profits are becoming unlimited. In a put option, the profits are only limited because the stock price cannot go lower than zero.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/10/72114afd8b6630732f02747a8bcbdcfb/47241723e1e155f10fad978e0db0e6c0/lateximg_large.png","width":753},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/10/72114afd8b6630732f02747a8bcbdcfb/47241723e1e155f10fad978e0db0e6c0/lateximg.png","width":376}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"3c1798f1-556e-401f-99c5-171d6f72295d","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolp